===============\nprint(\"Preprocessing light curve...\")\n# Remove NaNs and infinite values caused by data gaps or quality flags\nlc = lc.remove_nans()\n\n# Remove outliers using 3-sigma clipping to eliminate cosmic ray hits/flares\nlc_clean = lc.clip_outliers(sigma=3)\n\n# Flatten the light curve to remove long-term astrophysical/systematic trends.\n# A window length of 1 day is standard for TESS 30-min cadence data.\nlc_flat = lc_clean.flatten(window_length=1)\n\n# Extract time and flux arrays\ntime = lc_flat.time\nflux = lc_flat.flux\n\n# ==========================================\n# 3. Box Least Squares (BLS) Periodogram\n# ==========================================\nprint(\"Running Box Least Squares periodogram...\")\n# Define the period search space (0.5 to 25 days covers most short-period planets)\nperiods = np.linspace(0.5, 25, 10000) * u.day\n\n# Define transit duration grid (typical for close-in planets)\ndurations = np.linspace(0.05, 0.2, 10) * u.day\n\n# Initialize and run the BLS algorithm\nbls = BoxLeastSquares(time, flux)\nbls_power = bls.power(period=periods, duration=durations)\n\n# ==========================================\n# 4. Extract Best Period & Parameters\n# ==========================================\n# Find the index of the maximum BLS power\nbest_idx = np.argmax(bls_power.power)\n\nbest_period = bls_power.period[best_idx]\nbest_duration = bls_power.duration[best_idx]\nbest_t0 = bls_power.transit_time[best_idx]\nbest_depth = bls_power.depth[best_idx]\n\nprint(f\"\\n--- Detection Results ---\")\nprint(f\"Best Period:   {best_period.value:.4f} days\")\nprint(f\"Best Duration: {best_duration.value:.4f} days\")\nprint(f\"Transit Depth: {best_depth.value:.6f}\")\n\n# ==========================================\n# 5. Phase-fold the Light Curve\n# ==========================================\n# Fold the light curve using the detected period and transit epoch (T0)\nphase_folded = lc_flat.fold(period=best_period, epoch_time=best_t0)\n\n# ==========================================\n# 6. Visualization\n# ==========================================\nfig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 8))\n\n# Plot BLS Periodogram\nax1.plot(bls_power.period.value, bls_power.power, color='k', lw=0.5)\nax1.axvline(best_period.value, color='r', linestyle='--', \n            label=f'Best Period: {best_period.value:.4f} d')\nax1.set_xlabel('Period [days]')\nax1.set_ylabel('BLS Power')\nax1.set_title('Box Least Squares Periodogram')\nax1.legend()\n\n# Plot Phase-folded Light Curve\nax2.scatter(phase_folded.phase.value, phase_folded.flux, s=2, alpha=0.5, color='k')\nax2.set_xlabel('Phase')\nax2.set_ylabel('Normalized Flux')\nax2.set_title(f'Phase-folded Light Curve (P = {best_period.value:.4f} days)')\n\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n```\n\n### Key Steps Explained:\n1. **Preprocessing (`flatten` & `clip_outliers`)**: Raw TESS data contains stellar variability, spacecraft pointing drift, and cosmic ray hits. Flattening removes the low-frequency trends, while sigma-clipping removes high-frequency outliers, ensuring the BLS algorithm focuses strictly on transit-like dips.\n2. **Period & Duration Grids**: BLS requires a grid of trial periods and trial durations. The period grid is set from 0.5 to 25 days (fitting within a standard ~27-day TESS sector), and the duration grid spans typical hot-Jupiter to super-Earth transit lengths.\n3. **`BoxLeastSquares.power()`**: This computes the BLS statistic for every combination of period and duration, returning the period, transit time ($T_0$), depth, and duration that maximize the signal.\n4. **Phase-folding**: Once the period and $T_0$ are found, `lightkurve`'s `.fold()` method wraps the time series so that all transits align at phase 0, making visual confirmation and subsequent transit modeling (e.g., using `batman` or `exoplanet`) straightforward.", "solver_finish_reason": "stop"}
